# Dataset import
# Read in NYSE data from url
url = "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/ucla-econ-425t/2023winter/master/slides/data/NYSE.csv"
s = requests.get(url).content.decode('utf-8')
NYSE = pd.read_csv(io.StringIO(s), index_col = 0)

Dow Jones return (DJ_return, $r_t$): This is the difference between the log of the Dow Jones Industrial Index on consecutive trading days.

Log trading volume (log_volume, $v_t$): This is the fraction of all outstanding shares that are traded on that day, relative to a 100-day moving average of past turnover, on the log scale.

Log volatility (log_volatility, $z_t$): This is based on the absolute values of daily price movements.

Statement of Purpose¶

Forecast daily $v_t$ for dates 1980-1-1 to 1986-12-31 using training set of dates 1962-12-03 to 1979-12-31. This project will implement the following forecasting methods:

  1. Baseline straw man, where $\hat v_t = v_{t-1}$
  1. Autoregression($L$) model, where $L=5$
  1. Autoregression($L$) model, where $L=5$ with tuned multi-layer perceptron
  1. Long short-term memory forecaster with $L=5$
  1. Random forest algorithm

  1. Boosting algorithm

    6a. Boosting algo. (Scikit-learn)

    6b. Boosting algo. (XGBoost)

Train/Test Split of Dataset¶

In [8]:
# Lag predictors for L = 5
for i in range(1,6):
    Lag_Label = 'log_volume_lag' + str(i)
    NYSE[Lag_Label] = NYSE['log_volume'].shift(i)

# Split
Train = NYSE[NYSE['train'] == True].drop(columns = ['train'])
Test = NYSE[NYSE['train'] == False].drop(columns = ['train'])

Method: Baseline Strawman¶

In [9]:
# Baseline train/test split
Train_Baseline = pd.DataFrame({
    'v_t': Train['log_volume'],
    'v_t_lag1': Train['log_volume'].shift(1),
})

Test_Baseline = pd.DataFrame({
    'v_t': Test['log_volume'],
    'v_t_lag1': Test['log_volume'].shift(1),
})
In [10]:
# Baseline model
imputer = IterativeImputer(random_state = 1998, max_iter = 100)

Train_X = imputer.fit_transform(Train_Baseline['v_t_lag1'].values.reshape(-1,1))
Train_Y = Train_Baseline['v_t'].values.reshape(-1,1)

Test_X = imputer.fit_transform(Test_Baseline['v_t_lag1'].values.reshape(-1,1))
Test_Y = Test_Baseline['v_t'].values.reshape(-1,1)

n_folds = 10
Baseline_CV = cross_validate(LinearRegression(), Train_X, Train_Y, 
                             scoring = ('r2','neg_root_mean_squared_error'), 
                             cv=TimeSeriesSplit(n_folds))
Pred_Train_Y = LinearRegression().fit(Train_X, Train_Y).predict(Train_Y)
Pred_Y = LinearRegression().fit(Train_X, Train_Y).predict(Test_X)

Baseline_Test = (mean_squared_error(Test_Y, Pred_Y, squared = False), r2_score(Test_Y,Pred_Y))

# Evaluating CV performance
print('CV Training Performance:')
print(f"    RMSE Score is approximately {np.mean(-Baseline_CV['test_neg_root_mean_squared_error'])}")
print(f"    R-Squared is approximately {np.mean(Baseline_CV['test_r2'])}")


# Evaluating model performance
print('Testing Performance:')
print(f"     RMSE is approximately {Baseline_Test[0]}")
print(f"     R-Squared is approximately {Baseline_Test[1]}")
print('\n')

## AR(5) CV Results
# Cross-validation results
cv_res = pd.DataFrame({
    "alpha": np.array(search_AR5.cv_results_["param_model__alpha"]),
    "l1_ratio": np.array(search_AR5.cv_results_["param_model__l1_ratio"]),
    "rmse": -search_AR5.cv_results_["mean_test_score"]})

plt.figure()
sns.relplot(data = cv_res, x = "alpha", y = "rmse", hue = 'l1_ratio').set(
    xlabel = "alpha", ylabel = "CV RMSE", xscale = "log");
plt.show()

print(f'The best estimator is {search_AR5.best_estimator_}')
print('\n')

print('AR(5) MODEL RESULTS')
# Evaluating CV performance
Pred_Train_Y = search_AR5.best_estimator_.predict(Train_X)
print('CV Training Performance:')
print(f"    Best RMSE Score is approximately {-search_AR5.best_score_}")
print(f"    Best R-Squared is approximately {r2_score(Train_Y, Pred_Train_Y)}")

# Evaluating model performance
Pred_Y = search_AR5.best_estimator_.predict(Test_X)
RMSE = mean_squared_error(Test_Y, Pred_Y, squared = False)
print('Testing Performance:')
print(f"     RMSE is approximately {RMSE}")
print(f"     R-Squared is approximately {r2_score(Test_Y, Pred_Y)}")
print('\n')
